        <section class="section-content section-contribution" id="section-contribution">
          <h3 class="section-title">
            Contribution to Provident Fund & Pension Accounts
            <small>...under EPS 95 / EPF 1952 Schemes</small>
          </h3>
          <p>For a salaried person, contributions to the EPF offer a lot of benefits. It is one of the safest debt instruments available in India. It benefits from a good tax status, being E-E-E (exempt-exempt-exempt).Interest earned on EPF is completely tax free.On retirement, maturity proceeds are also not taxed. This makes this instrument very salary-friendly. It offers the equivalent of a high pre-tax rate of guaranteed interest - earning 8.60% tax free is the equivalent of a 12.28% interest rate considering someone paying 30% tax.</p>
          <p>The contributions payable by the employer under the Scheme shall be at the rate of 12 percent of the basic wages, dearness allowance (including the cash value of any food concession) and retaining allowance (if any) payable to each employee to whom the Scheme applies.The contribution payable by the employee under the Scheme, shall be equal to the contribution payable by the employer.</p>
          <p>The contributions shall be calculated on the total of basic wages, dearness allowance and retaining allowance (if any)] actually drawn during the whole month whether paid on daily, weekly, fortnightly or monthly basis. Each contribution shall be calculated to the nearest rupee, 50 paise or more to be counted as the next higher rupee and fraction of a rupee less than 50 paise to be ignored. </p>
          <p>EPF is a very long term investment instrument. Forshort term financial goals, funding by withdrawals from EPF is not advisable. If goals are in fact primarily short term, as is the case with young couples, or parents funding their children’s educations in a few years, investing the minimum amount in EPF, and channelizing remaining funds towards a more liquid instrument, keeping risk appetite and goal time horizon in mind is advised.</p>
        </section>

